snippet.textDisplay: Ladies and gentlemen, PLEASE stop using coconut oil on your hair. The molecules are too large to penetrate the hair shaft and will only coat your hair shaft, if you are lightening over coconut oil, it will only inhibit the lightening process and will be harder to remove the pigments inside your cortex. If you want an oil to penetrate and moisturize your hair, use sweet almond oil, jojoba oil, etc. They have smaller molecules and will penetrate the hair shaft and give you the results you’re looking for!
snippet.textOriginal: Ladies and gentlemen, PLEASE stop using coconut oil on your hair. The molecules are too large to penetrate the hair shaft and will only coat your hair shaft, if you are lightening over coconut oil, it will only inhibit the lightening process and will be harder to remove the pigments inside your cortex. If you want an oil to penetrate and moisturize your hair, use sweet almond oil, jojoba oil, etc. They have smaller molecules and will penetrate the hair shaft and give you the results you’re looking for!

snippet.textDisplay: Coconut oil doesn't help in the long run, you still have to take care of your hair. But in the bleaching process, I have noticed coconut oil makes my hair super soft and strong after I bleach. I've been bleaching my hair for 12 years straight , and last year I started using coconut oil before I bleach.  Usually my hair would get stringy and break easily and I would have to wait a week or so before I bleached it again, but with coconut oil my hair is strong and I can bleach it twice in the same day with little to no breakage.
